# The Complete Register of Works

A record of what survives of the greatest that has been thought and written by *Homo sapiens* across the roughly three hundred thousand years of the species' existence — five hundred and thirty-six works, drawn from some forty-five language-worlds and nine chronological epochs, each admitted because the sustained testimony of specialist scholarship identifies it as a genuine achievement of the human intellect or imagination or both. What follows is the canon stripped of annotation, argument, and apparatus: the works alone, in the order and grouping in which they stand. It is offered for the reader who wants the whole shape of the thing at a glance, and for the reader who, having read the entries, wishes to hold the list in the mind as a single object. Everything that justifies these choices is set out in the preceding pages; here there is only the record.

